[[File:Screenshot Harmonized Novel text 20180120.jpg|thumb|A China novel website has to harmonize the numbers "eight" and "nine", as the two numbers can be interpreted as the year 1989, even though the original meaning of the figures mean "80 to 90% sure"{{clarify|date=May 2018}}.]] '''River crab''' ({{zh|c={{linktext|河|蟹}}|p={{linktext|hé|xiè}}}}) and '''harmonious/harmonize/harmonization''' ({{zh| links=no|c={{linktext|和|谐}}|p={{linktext|hé|xié}}}}) are [[Internet slang]] terms created by [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] [[netizen]]s in reference to [[Internet censorship in the People's Republic of China|Internet censorship]] or the other [[Censorship in the People's Republic of China|censorship]] of China. In [[Standard Mandarin|Chinese Mandarin]], the word "river crab" (河蟹), which originally means [[Chinese mitten crab]], [[Homophonic puns in Mandarin Chinese|sounds similar]] to "harmonious/harmonize/harmonization" ({{zh| links=no|c=和谐}}) in the word "[[harmonious society]]" (和谐社会), ex-Chinese leader [[Hu Jintao]]'s signature ideology.<ref name="nytimes">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/12/world/asia/12beast.html?em|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|author=Michael Wines|title=A Dirty Pun Tweaks China’s Online Censors |date=2009-03-11|accessdate=2010-10-30}}</ref>
==Terms== The 2004 [[Chinese Communist Party]] announcement of the goal of constructing a "harmonious society" has been cited by the [[Government of the People's Republic of China|government of China]] as the reason for Internet censorship. As a result, Chinese netizens began to use the word "harmonious/harmonize/harmonization" (和谐) as a euphemism for censorship when the word for censorship itself was censored, particularly on [[bulletin board system|BBSs]]. Following this, the word "harmonious" itself was censored, at which point Chinese netizens began to use the word for "river crab", a [[Homophonic puns in Mandarin Chinese|near homophone]] for "harmonious". In a further complication of meaning, sometimes '''aquatic product''' ({{zh| links=no|c={{linktext|水|产}}}}) is used in place of "river crab".
These euphemisms are also used as verbs. For example, instead of saying something has been censored, one might say "it has been harmonized" ({{zh| c=被和谐了}}) or "it has been river-crabbed" ({{zh| c=被河蟹了}}). The widespread use of "river crab" by Chinese netizens represents a sarcastic defiance against official discourse and censorship. Some observers, however, have warned that the practice may also reproduce domination, since it does not aim for the abolition of censorship. The sensitive words will remain silent as such, and as a result the everyday reappropriation of official language creates the conditions for the latter's perpetuation.<ref>Nordin, Astrid and Richud, Lisa (2014), "Subverting official language and discourse in China? Type river crab for harmony," China Information 28, 1 (March): 47-67.</ref>
